I went for the Manapua and I was not disappointed. 40 years ago it cost $0.25 for one from the food truck that frequented our school. Today it cost $1.90: a bargain compared to the real estate cost increases in Hawaii over the past 40 years.  Their hours are limited and Char Hung Sut is not a restaurant.  They have a very limited number of options, but they do have soda in a cooler if you need something to drink. Your food is placed in a cardboard box and tied shut - everything is carry out.  Their operation is very basic, fun to watch, and efficient. They take your order, get your food, take your money and you are expected to move on so someone else can get their food.  Parking is street parking, and because you’re in Chinatown you might want to take the time to explore a bit while you’re there.  The manapua is great, and I expect the rest of what they do is very good as well. I hope I have the time, and appetite given all the other great food options in the area.

Oh dear God i love this place. Been coming for 25 years. I get the manapua, mai tai soo and pork hash. Ask for shoyu (soy sauce) and mustard to dip your pork hash in. Know what you want and how many before you get in line. They move very fast. They write want you want on a piece of paper and then you move to the register to pay and get your box of yum. When you walk in, yes, it looks like you are walking into the back of a chinese bakery. Your not. That is the front of char hung sut. Go in on the right door, out on the left. Dont double park. They are closed tuesdays. Call in advance if you want a big order. If you are near closing they do run out of things. If you tell them you are taking it to the mainland they will pack it with some cardboard so it wont crush and tie it with a bit of a handle to make it easier to carry. This is a takeout counter only, not a restaurant with seating or tables.  You are literally walking into a working kitchen with many stacks of large metal dim sum steamer trays and a checkout counter to buy to-go only.  You will walk right next to mostly ladies hand shaping meat dumplings at stations next to the cash register.  There is barely an entrance, let alone one that is handicapped accessible; there are signs at the door warning you to watch your step and to not hit your head walking in.  It is quite an experience to visit this dusty shop churning out old-school Cantonese Chinese style dim sum with a Hawaiian twist.  Most dim sum found in California, particularly the San Francisco Bay Area, is now in the more fashionable and popular Hong Kong teahouse style.  The big giveaway is the difference in the shape of the steamed buns or manapua.  The buns here have pillowy smooth and round tops.  Hong Kong style steamed buns have semi-open, "burst-open" tops.

I decided to try this place out based off a co-workers recommendation.  He spoke highly about this place, but in the end, I wasn’t as big of a fan as he.  I saw that it was a little hole in the wall and was prepared to jump out and just pick up our order and hele on.  So we called our order in one Saturday afternoon on our way down from a hike.  It really is this small hole in the wall place.  No storefront, you just walk in and you’re surrounded by boxes and people cooking and prepping food.  When I got there, the order was ready to be picked up still hot and steamy.  NOTE:  If you are sharing the food and want it to be packaged a certain way, just ask them over the phone.  I asked for an extra box so I could separate my mom’s order and they were going to charge me so I just asked for a plastic bag for free.  We ordered the manapua, the pork hash, and some fried noodles.  I was totally excited about the manapua because my coworker talked it up, so I took a big bite.  It was all bread.  The whole bite.  So I took another and finally found the meat.  I thought maybe the meat wasn’t centered and I just got the bread side, but nope.  There was so much bread in comparison to the meat.  It might have been okay if there was something special about the bread, but there wasn’t.  It was soft but bland.  The meat was very flavorful though, just not a lot of it.  The noodles was the second thing I was excited about it.  I took a bite, and it tasted like smoke but not in a good way.  Like someone was smoking a cigarette and was blowing it into the noodles and flicking their ashes in there too.  I thought maybe I was being too mean, so I let my husband try it, and my mom try it.  They both said the same thing.  Then, I put it to the ultimate test and let my toddler have a go at it.  My toddler who loves noodle in any form and flavor, would not eat it after taking a single bite and spitting it out.  I don’t know man, maybe some people like to eat noodles that take like smoke and nothing else, but I think I’ll pass.  The pork hash was like an after thought when we were ordering but it ended up being my favorite item.  The wrap wasn’t too dry and there was a lot of filling for the size of the wrap.  The pork filling had tons of flavor and was nice and juicy.  TLDR; SO, I won’t ever go back.  I would rather get my manapuas from Libbys or better yet, 7-11 or Chun Wah Kam as they are closer to home and have a good meat to bread ratio while still packing flavor in the meat.  I disliked the noodles and the pork hash, while the star of all the food, isn’t enough to get me to come all the way back to town to get.

Located on Pauahi on the left side going west, look for the sign and an opening. It's not in a great area but not too bad in the day and worth the trip.  No parking unless you park in a municipal, get lucky and find street parking or you get dropped off so you can run in and out (few places that someone can park and wait for you for a few minutes).  You go down a couple of stairs and you're transported into a huge room that looks like you walked into a kitchen. Boxes piled high, the old Chinese ladies folding pork hash by hand (their hands are so fast, it's rhythmic to watch them) and an old school cash register. Yup, you're in the right place.  There's a small menu with prices on the top right when you come in. Someone will take your order and then grab your order. You can call ahead for large orders. Cash only.  Best pork hash on the island, hands down. No fatty chunks and not overly greasy. The pork isn't too salty or sweet. The half moon and pepeiao are also good too. All $0.90 each (I remember when it was $0.65 which was over 5 years ago).  The char siu manapua is a good size for $1.70 ($1 over 5 years ago) and has a good amount of shredded char siu that's not overly seasoned.  Also I like to get gon lol mein and chow fun in the standard quart take out containers if I'm hungrier for $6.50 ($5.25 over 5 years ago).  Hot mustard is $0.10 additional but a must get.  One of my all time favorite placard for a fast breakfast or snacks!  ******** Go to Char Hung Sut Best pork hash on the island. Make sure you get cash.

Cheap, good taste, friendly folks...walk right in the kitchen and take a box to the canal. Great place to have our last lunch on the island before heading back to the mainland.
Best manupua I have had in a long time!
Awesome manapua! Always delicious!

I am 38 years old and have been going there since I was like 5 or 6 years old with my grandfather. The memories of going there picking out all my favorite dim sum. My whole family goes there as well as our children. They are friendly and knows us when we come in. Love love love
to go food, you order at counter and take away, no sit down. very good flavours, char siu bao, dumplings, marvelous tastiness !
Best dim sum I've had in a long while. Take out only just a heads up.
Nothing like a family business run for over sixty years to serve you the best manapua in the world!!!
Excellant food fast service
